Final Project Analysis Code and Final Report¶

Project Title: Never-use of long acting reversible contraception (LARC) among U.S. women aged 15-49 years

Student Name: Payal Chakraborty

Introduction¶

Long-acting reversible contraception (LARC) is a class of birth control method that provides long lasting pregnancy prevention. There are two types of LARC methods, the intrauterine device (IUD) and the implant. The IUD gets inserted into the uterus, and the implant gets inserted into the skin of the upper arm. The methods are effective at preventing pregnancy because they remove the user error component of birth control, which other methods do not have: for example, for the birth control pill, the user has to remember to take it every day at the same time.

The use of LARC has steadily increased over the years, from 6% in 2002 to 14% in 2002 to 14% in 2014 [1-3]. Oral contracpetion is still the most commonly used form of contraception [1]. There is a disconnect between the high typical use effectiveness of LARC and low use.

The disconnect between effectiveness and use may be explained by the various barriers individuals may face in obtaining LARC. Cost and insurance coverage is a major barrier in LARC uptake. Although the 2010 Affordable Care Act should have removed some of these cost and insurance barriers, there have been challenges made to the contraception mandate [4] and people may not be aware that LARC is available at no cost to them [5]. Since using LARC requires a physician office visit for insertion, scheduling and getting an appointment is a barrier for many people [6]. Additionally lack of knowledge and unfavorable attitudes may be a barrier to use; for example, many people hold misconceptions about LARC, and many are uncomfortable with the idea of newer methods [7], or having an object in the body. Also, many providers themselves lack about knowledge about LARC, and some hold incorrect beliefs that LARC is inappropriate for some women, and not others [8-12].

Reproductive coercion, especially targeting women of color, is also a huge problem, and can be a significant barrier to LARC uptake [13,14]. Reproductive coercion is rooted in the history in the US. In the 20th century, the US had forced sterilization programs targeting the poor, the disabled, criminals, and people of color. Nowadays, since LARC requires a physician for insertion and removal, sometimes physicians have refused to remove LARC because of their beliefs about whether their patients should be able to reproduce [15], undermining patient autonomy. Experiences like this deter many people from trying LARC in fear of not being able to get it removed, even if it could potentially benefit them.

Among users who willfully use LARC, the method has shown to have high efficacy, benefits, and acceptability. Anyone who wants LARC, should be able to use it. This project falls under the overarching goal of increasing accessibility of LARC for those who would most benefit from it and want it. The specific objectives of this project are explained in the next section.

Objectives¶

Specifically, the objectives of this project are two-fold:

  1. The first objective is to identify the most important features of ever LARC use among ever contraception users.
  2. The second objective is to predict LARC use. This will help identify who might benefit most from LARC and from targeted outreach for LARC use. An indicator of lifetime use may be informative for targeting strategies for contraceptive counseling.

Data Set: The National Survey of Family Growth (NSFG)¶

The National Survey of Family Growth (NSFG) is a national survey in the US. It is conducted by the US Centers for Disease Control and Prevention (CDC) in collaboration with other government agencies. The survey copies topics such as family life, marriage and divorce, pregnancy, infertility, use of contracpetion, and general and reproductive health. It is a publically available dataset and can be found on the US CDC website (https://www.cdc.gov/nchs/nsfg/index.htm).

The survey has been going on for many years, and has evolved over time. The first survey was conducted in 1973. Originally the survey was representative of women aged 15-44 in the U.S. In 2002, the survey expanded to include a sample of men that is independent from the women. In 2015, the survey expanded to ages 15-49 years. The response rate for recent years is about 69%, which is very high for a national survey. The administration of the survey is voluntary, and it is conducted via in-person interviews at participants' homes.

The NSFG is a widely used survey and is used by many different people: scholar and researchers, government agencies, and the media.

For this final project, I use the 2015-2017 survey. A total of 5,554 women participated in the 2015-2017 survey. The population of interest for this study is ever contraception users, so the final analytical sample consists of 4,904 women.

Summary of Analysis Plan¶

Primary Outcome: The primary outcome of this analysis is ever use of LARC (yes/no). It is a binary variable and it is derived from ever use of IUD and ever use of implant. This variable has never been used in the NSFG data set.

Primary Predictors: There are several predictors of interest for this project. They fall under the following six categories: demographics (e.g. age, education, race, income, rural/urban residence, etc.), substance use (e.g. alcohol use, drug use), health care access (health insurance status, having a regular provider, place of health care seeking, etc.), relationship history (marital status, number of sexual partners, sex education, etc.), housing insecurity status (e.g. homelessness, inability to pay rent, etc.), and religious characteristics (religious affiliation, frequency of attending religious services now/past, etc.).

Analysis Summary: My primary model of interest is the neural network. I try using PCA and f-score method to reduce dimensions. About 23% of the sample has the outcome of interest, so I use class weights or resampling methods (synthetic minority oversampling technique [SMOTE] or undersampling) to deal with class imbalance. To tune the model, I adjust the number of input features, number of nodes, number of layers, droupout rate, learning rate, hidden layer activation functions, batch size, and number of epochs. To improve my prediction I try two enesmble learning methods, primarily ones that use the same model on different samples of the data, and then combine them. I use k-fold cross validation ensemble and bootstrap aggregation (bagging) ensemble, with logistic regression as the meta classifier for stacking the models. Finally, I compare my results with my final neural network model and more traditional methods, specifically logistic regression and a random forest classifier.

from imblearn.over_sampling import SMOTE
def SMOTEsampling(X_train,Y_train):
    sm=SMOTE(random_state=42)
    X_train, Y_train = sm.fit_sample(X_train, Y_train)
    return X_train,Y_train

from imblearn.under_sampling import RandomUnderSampler
def downsampling(X_train,Y_train):
    rds = RandomUnderSampler(random_state=42)
    X_train, Y_train = rds.fit_resample(X_train, Y_train)
    return X_train,Y_train

Wide Model¶

First, I started with one layer, and all of my input features included. I tuned the drop out rate, learning rate, number of nodes, and elu vs. relu activation function. I tried many many of combinations of all of these things (not shown for the purposes of simplicity). I easily get overfitting, so I did not have too much options in adding nodes to improve the accuracy. Even though the below model uses all 114 features, I also tried using the PCA version of the data with reduced features. Any reduction of features reduced the accuracy of this model, besides the two variables I removed using the f-score method (below). Thus, the following model is the final model I chose for the best wide model.

In [23]:
seed_everything(SEED)
def create_model():
    # create model
    model = tf.keras.Sequential([
    tf.keras.layers.Input(N_FEATURES),
    tf.keras.layers.BatchNormalization(),
    tf.keras.layers.Dropout(0.1),
    tfa.layers.WeightNormalization(tf.keras.layers.Dense(80, activation='relu')),
    tf.keras.layers.BatchNormalization(),
    tf.keras.layers.Dropout(0.1),
    tfa.layers.WeightNormalization(tf.keras.layers.Dense(1, activation="sigmoid"))
    ])
    # Compile model
    model.compile(loss='binary_crossentropy', optimizer=tf.keras.optimizers.Adam(learning_rate = 0.0001), metrics=['accuracy'])
    return model

model = create_model()

Deep Model¶

With the deep model, the elu activation function worked the best. When I add nodes or layers, I get slight overfitting. When I increase the dropout rate, to fix the overfitting, then accuracy goes down, lower than even the best wide model above. So then to deal with the overfitting, I introduced the PCA to reduce the number of input features. I first tried 20, then increased it to 32, and then I landed on 40. The model below is where I stopped in this cycle. For example, in the model before this model, my number of input features was 32. I had 2 hidden layers with 16 and 4 nodes; the dropout rate was 0.1; the number of epochs was 500, and the batch size was 200. This model gave an accuracy of 0.6008 withb slight overfitting. Then I increased the drop out to 0.12 and got an accuracy of 0.5926 and less overfitting. Then I increased the number of features to 40, and got an accuracy of 0.60896, with slight overftting again. Then when I increased the drop out to 0.2, the accuracy went back down to, but then reduced the overfitting problem by a bit, but it is still there. Since this was going in circles, I decided to stop at this model and try the next strategy.

Deep model with PCA to reduce features and class weights to deal with imbalance. Here you will see the slight overfitting problem. If you try to handle the overfitting with increasing the droupout, the accuracy decreases.

In [31]:
seed_everything(SEED)
def create_deep_model():
    # create model
    model_deep = tf.keras.Sequential([
    tf.keras.layers.Input(N_PCA_FEATURES),
    tf.keras.layers.BatchNormalization(),
    tf.keras.layers.Dropout(0.2),
    tfa.layers.WeightNormalization(tf.keras.layers.Dense(16, activation='elu')),
    tf.keras.layers.BatchNormalization(),
    tf.keras.layers.Dropout(0.2),
    tfa.layers.WeightNormalization(tf.keras.layers.Dense(4, activation='elu')),
    tf.keras.layers.BatchNormalization(),
    tf.keras.layers.Dropout(0.2),
    tfa.layers.WeightNormalization(tf.keras.layers.Dense(1, activation="sigmoid"))
    ])
    # Compile model
    model_deep.compile(loss='binary_crossentropy', optimizer=tf.keras.optimizers.Adam(learning_rate = 0.0001), metrics=['accuracy'])
    return model_deep

model_deep = create_deep_model()

Deep model with PCA to reduce features and SMOTE resampling to deal with imbalance. Here you can see that the validation model seems to have higher; this is a common result with SMOTE resampling. The test accuracy is higher than the wide model, about 72.5%. However, while the specificity is high (91%) the sensitivity is very low (18%). This is shown in the code below. Adding another layer beyond this makes the accuracy go down; adding more nodes in the first layer doesn't improve the accuracy by much, and adding more nodes in the other layers makes the accuracy go down. This is the best deep model. Also, note that I have updated this best deep model compared to what I presented in my slides, since I have been working on this model more.

seed_everything(SEED)
def create_deep_model():
    # create model
    model_deep = tf.keras.Sequential([
    tf.keras.layers.Input(N_FEATURES),
    tf.keras.layers.BatchNormalization(),
    tf.keras.layers.Dropout(0.12),
    tfa.layers.WeightNormalization(tf.keras.layers.Dense(64, activation='elu')),
    tf.keras.layers.BatchNormalization(),
    tf.keras.layers.Dropout(0.12),
    tfa.layers.WeightNormalization(tf.keras.layers.Dense(32, activation='elu')),
    tf.keras.layers.BatchNormalization(),
    tf.keras.layers.Dropout(0.12),
    tfa.layers.WeightNormalization(tf.keras.layers.Dense(16, activation='elu')),
    tf.keras.layers.BatchNormalization(),
    tf.keras.layers.Dropout(0.12),
    #tfa.layers.WeightNormalization(tf.keras.layers.Dense(4, activation='elu')),
    #tf.keras.layers.BatchNormalization(),
    #tf.keras.layers.Dropout(0.12),
    tfa.layers.WeightNormalization(tf.keras.layers.Dense(1, activation="sigmoid"))
    ])
    # Compile model
    model_deep.compile(loss='binary_crossentropy', optimizer=tf.keras.optimizers.Adam(learning_rate = 0.0001), metrics=['accuracy'])
    return model_deep

model_deep = create_deep_model()

Important Note: Careful removal of features using f-score method worked better than batch removal of features using PCA.

Better to go deeper or wider?¶

I have tried two strategies for building a neural network: getting the best wide neural network and getting the best deep neural network. The best wide network has one hidden layer (with relu activation function) with 80 notes, with class weights to deal with class imbalance. The best deep network has 64, 32, and 16 hidden layers (with elu activation function), and uses SMOTE resampling to deal with class imbalance. The best wide model achieves and accuracy of about 60% while the best deep layer achieves an accuracy of about 73%. However, the best wide model has more balanced sensitivity and specificity, while the best deep model has high specificity and very low sensitivity (more details on the sensitivity and specificity shown in the next section). Thus, the wider model is the better model, since a more balanced sensitivity and specificity is more desirable for this research problem. I will try to later improve this model using ensemble learning.

def confusion_metrics (conf_matrix):
    TP = conf_matrix[1][1]
    TN = conf_matrix[0][0]
    FP = conf_matrix[0][1]
    FN = conf_matrix[1][0]
    print('True Positives:', TP)
    print('True Negatives:', TN)
    print('False Positives:', FP)
    print('False Negatives:', FN)
    
    # accuracy
    conf_accuracy = (float (TP+TN) / float(TP + TN + FP + FN))
    
    # mis-classification
    conf_misclassification = 1- conf_accuracy
    
    # sensitivity (recall)
    conf_sensitivity = (TP / float(TP + FN))
    # specificity
    conf_specificity = (TN / float(TN + FP))
    
    # precision (PPV)
    conf_precision = (TP / float(TP + FP))
    
    # f_1 score
    conf_f1 = 2 * ((conf_precision * conf_sensitivity) / (conf_precision + conf_sensitivity))
    print('-'*20)
    print(f'Accuracy: {round(conf_accuracy,2)}') 
    print(f'Mis-Classification: {round(conf_misclassification,2)}') 
    print(f'Sensitivity (Recall): {round(conf_sensitivity,2)}') 
    print(f'Specificity: {round(conf_specificity,2)}') 
    print(f'Precision: {round(conf_precision,2)}')
    print(f'f_1 Score: {round(conf_f1,2)}')

Try Ensemble Learning Methods¶

Source for applying ensemble methods: https://machinelearningmastery.com/how-to-create-a-random-split-cross-validation-and-bagging-ensemble-for-deep-learning-in-keras/

Source for stacking models: https://machinelearningmastery.com/stacking-ensemble-for-deep-learning-neural-networks/

In this section, I try two popular ensemble learning methods to see if these methods can improve the model performance as a proof of concept. Both methods involve training different samples of the dataset. The two methods that I try are (1) k-fold cross-validation and (2) bagging (or bootrstrap aggregation).

First, I re-specify the model:

In [53]:
seed_everything(1234)
def evaluate_model(trainX, trainy, testX, testy):
    # define model
    model = tf.keras.Sequential([
    tf.keras.layers.Input(N_FEATURES),
    tf.keras.layers.BatchNormalization(),
    tf.keras.layers.Dropout(0.1),
    tfa.layers.WeightNormalization(tf.keras.layers.Dense(84, activation='relu')),
    tf.keras.layers.BatchNormalization(),
    tf.keras.layers.Dropout(0.1),
    tfa.layers.WeightNormalization(tf.keras.layers.Dense(1, activation="sigmoid"))
    ])
    model.compile(loss='binary_crossentropy', optimizer=tf.keras.optimizers.Adam(learning_rate = 0.0001), metrics=['binary_accuracy'])
    # fit model
    model.fit(trainX, trainy, epochs=10, batch_size=30, class_weight=class_weight, verbose=0)
    # evaluate the model
    _, test_acc = model.evaluate(testX, testy, verbose=0)
    return model, test_acc

Define functions that I will use the stack the models:

In [54]:
def stacked_dataset(members, inputX):
    stackX = None
    for model in members:
        # make prediction
        yhat = model.predict(inputX, verbose=0)
        # stack predictions into [rows, members, probabilities]
        if stackX is None:
            stackX = yhat
        else:
            stackX = dstack((stackX, yhat))
    # flatten predictions to [rows, members x probabilities]
    stackX = stackX.reshape((stackX.shape[0], stackX.shape[1]*stackX.shape[2]))
    return stackX
In [55]:
# fit a model based on the outputs from the ensemble members
def fit_stacked_model(members, inputX, inputy):
    # create dataset using ensemble
    stackedX = stacked_dataset(members, inputX)
    # fit standalone model
    model_s = LogisticRegression(class_weight=class_weight)
    model_s.fit(stackedX, inputy)
    return model_s
In [56]:
def stacked_prediction(members, model, inputX):
    # create dataset using ensemble
    stackedX = stacked_dataset(members, inputX)
    # make a prediction
    yhat = model.predict(stackedX)
    yhat_prob = model.predict_proba(stackedX)
    return yhat, yhat_prob

Bagging (Bootstrap Aggregation) Ensemble¶

The steps for the bagging method are similar. Here, I use the "resample" function from the sklearn package to coduct the bootstrap sampling.

In [57]:
from sklearn.utils import resample
# multiple train-test splits
n_splits = 10
b_scores, b_members = list(), list()
for _ in range(n_splits):
    # select indexes
    ix = [i for i in range(len(X))]
    train_ix = resample(ix, replace=True, n_samples=2000, random_state=42)
    test_ix = [x for x in ix if x not in train_ix]
    # select data
    trainX, trainy = X.iloc[train_ix], y.iloc[train_ix]
    testX, testy = X.iloc[test_ix], y.iloc[test_ix]
    # evaluate model
    model, test_acc = evaluate_model(trainX, trainy, testX, testy)
    print('>%.3f' % test_acc)
    b_scores.append(test_acc)
    b_members.append(model)

# Calculating class probabilities
pred_proba = [i[1] for i in logreg.predict_proba(X_test)]
pred_df = pd.DataFrame({'true_values': y_test,
                        'pred_probs':pred_proba})

# Thresholds
thresholds = np.linspace(0, 1, 200)

# Calculate sensitivity. (True positive rate.)
def TPR(df, true_col, pred_prob_col, threshold):
    true_positive = df[(df[true_col] == 1) & (df[pred_prob_col] >= threshold)].shape[0]
    false_negative = df[(df[true_col] == 1) & (df[pred_prob_col] < threshold)].shape[0]
    return true_positive / (true_positive + false_negative)
    
# Calculate 1 - specificity. (False positive rate.)
def FPR(df, true_col, pred_prob_col, threshold):
    true_negative = df[(df[true_col] == 0) & (df[pred_prob_col] <= threshold)].shape[0]
    false_positive = df[(df[true_col] == 0) & (df[pred_prob_col] > threshold)].shape[0]
    return 1 - (true_negative / (true_negative + false_positive))
    
# Calculate sensitivity & 1-specificity for each threshold between 0 and 1.
tpr_values = [TPR(pred_df, 'true_values', 'pred_probs', prob) for prob in thresholds]
fpr_values = [FPR(pred_df, 'true_values', 'pred_probs', prob) for prob in thresholds]

Discussion and Conclusions¶

Out of all the methods I tried, the neural network performed the best, specifically the wider model with a k-fold cross validation ensemble with k=5. Even though the best accuracy I could achieve was 65%, with 72% sensitivity and 63% specificity from the k-fold cross validation ensemble using the wide neural network, this result is extremely informative for the field. The NSFG is a widely used survey for contraception research, and a lot of people rely on this survey to study some of the more descriptive population-level characteristics that are relevant for contraception decision-making. In LARC research specifically, a lot of the descriptive research focuses on variables like parity and age. But this project suggests, that there are other factors that are more informative for LARC use that are not captured in the survey. For example, anecodotal stories play a role in individuals' decisions to use or not use LARC, but this was not asked in the survey. Furthermore, health behavioral models were not considered in the NSFG.

This paper (https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pmc/articles/PMC5373259/) by Roderique-Davies et al., explored behavioral factors that predict LARC use using survey questions that directly tied to these behaviors. The indivudal behavior concepts come from two well established health behavior theories: the health belief model and the theory of planned behavior. The concepts, including applications to LARC are summarized in the table below. This table was adapted from the Roderique-Davies et al. paper.

Behavior Concept LARC Application
Perceived susceptibility How likely a participant believed it was that she would become pregnant
Perceived severity Would becoming pregnant be a positive or negative thing?
Perceived benefits Perceived positive benefits of using LARC
Perceived barriers Embarrassment to ask and fear of using LARC
Health motivation How important not becoming pregnant was to the participant
Cues to action How influential a healthcare worker was in contraception choice
Attitude Degree to which attitude towards LARC is viewed positively or negatively
Subjective norm How partners approve or disapprove of LARC use
Perceived behavioral control Ease or difficulty of using LARC in terms of internal factors (e.g. its my choice) and external factors (its out of my control)
Self-efficacy Confidence in their own ability to use LARC

These health behavior theories were tested using survey questions in the Roderique-Davies et al. paper. Thus, future rounds of NSFG could easily add these types of questions into the survey so that the questions can be used to improve the model predictions.

Future Directions: Future directions of this research should seek to understand most important drivers of LARC and contraception decision making as well as add questions to NSFG about behavioral factors above.

Limitations: There are three main limitations in this study. First, this project uses self-reported data, so it is possible that respondents misunderstood the questions or did not respond truthfully to some of the questions. Second, I am limtied by the questions that were included in the NSFG survey, so inclusion of other questions not asked, such as the ones suggested in the table above, could improve the survey. Third, the data are imbalanced: just over 20% of the sample had the outcome of ever-LARC use. This made it challenging to train the data for a neural network.

Impact: First, this project highlights gaps in the current understanding of factors driving LARC use. Many rely on the NSFG to study contraception decision making. Based on the prediction metrics from this project, it is likely that the NSFG does not contain all types of questions that encompass contraception decision making. Second, this project addresses lack of access to LARC in a novel way, by pulling a range of data from NSFG and using state of the art machine learning methods to predict LARC ever use. Third, this is the first application of machine learning in contraception research. Finally, another big strength of this project is that this analysis uses nationally representative data.
